<h1>From Major General Artemas Ward</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Boston 4th May 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Your Letter of the twenty ninth of April is just come to hand. Agreeable to your desire I shall give an account of what has been done towards fortifying the Harbour. The Forts on Fort Hill in Boston, Charlestown Point, and Castle Point, are almost compleated, with a number of heavy Cannon mounted in each; a Work is in good forwardness on Noddles Island, and a Detachment of the Army is at work at Castle Island repairing the Batteries there. A number of Hulks are preparing to sink in the Channel. I have employed the Troops here to the greatest advantage in my power, have ordered all the Men not on actual duty to turn out upon fatigue every day, not allowing any superfluous Cooks nor Waiters; and upon receiving intelligence of a British Fleet being on its passage this way I directed all the Officers to turn out with their men upon the Works, which they chearfully complyed with and are constantly upon fatigue with their Men.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> I have set every wheel in motion which I could move to advantage, and shall neglect nothing in my power in order to give the Enemy a proper reception if they should pay us a visit.</p>
<p>I have inclosed a Return of this Division of the Army.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>I am to inform your Excellency that I have just received a
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-04-02-pb-0204">[204]</span>
Letter from the President of the Congress, by which I am informed the Congress has accepted my resignation.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> The sooner I am relieved the more agreeable it will be to me, as my health has declined much this Spring. I am Your Excellencys Obedient Humble Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Artemas Ward</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0168-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston ]">MHi</span>: Ward Papers.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Wards orders regarding waiters, cooks, and men not on guard duty were issued on 20 April. On 3 May Ward announced that sixty sail of British Ships with twelve thousand troops on board are on their way to Boston and ordered Every Officer, non-commissioned Officer &amp; private off duty . . . to turn out to fatigue until further orders (Wards Orderly Book, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston ]">MHi</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The return, which is dated 4 May and signed by Brigade Major Peleg Wadsworth, reports a total of 2,289 rank and file in the five regiments under Wards command at Boston, Charlestown, Dorchester, and Beverly. Of that number 1,691 men were fit for duty. In addition, the regiments had 134 commissioned officers, 20 staff officers, and 205 noncommissioned officers. Another 80 in those three categories were absent or unfit for duty (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-04-02-0168-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>For Wards resignation see Hancock to Ward, 26 April 1776, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Paul H. Smith et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Letters of Delegates to Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;. 26 vols. Washington, D.C., 19762000. ]">Smith, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letters of Delegates</span></span>, 3:58485, and <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:300.</p>

</div>
